\[
\pdv{u}{t}+ku\pdv{u}{x}=0\qc t>t_{0}\qc x\in(-\infty,+\infty)
\]

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

, it is called the 
\noun on
inviscid Burgers equation
\noun default

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 could be any physical quantity, while the wave speed 
\begin_inset Formula $ku$
\end_inset

 must has a dimension of speed.
 It is better to keep writing the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, even when 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since PDE
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuasilinearWaveEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is the nonlinearized version of PDE
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearWaveEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is natural to solve it locally as what we have done for its linear
 counterpart, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find the characteristic curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 remains unchanged along any characteristic curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Get the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like in the linear case, the characteristic curve passing through 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{0},x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and above 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the solution of the following IVP:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\dv{x}{t} & =a(u)\qc t>t_{0}\\
x(t_{0}) & =x_{0}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

To find its solution, we need to prove the following fact first:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t,x)$
\end_inset

 remains unchanged along a characteristic curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume the characteristic curves do not intersect with each other, at least
 in a finite time period 
\begin_inset Formula $(t_{0},t_{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Then, along any characteristic curve:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\dv{u(t,x)}{t} & =\pdv{u(t,x)}{t}+\dv{x(t,x)}{t}\pdv{u(t,x)}{x}\\
 & =\pdv{u(t,x)}{t}+a(u(t,x))\pdv{u(t,x)}{x}=0
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

The last equality is implied by PDE
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QuasilinearWaveEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this fact, we know the characteristic curves are straight lines
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{x-x_{0}}{t-t_{0}}=a(u)\label{eq:CharCurveOfQuasilinearWaveEquation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whose slopes are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(u(t,x))=a\left(u_{0}\left(x_{0}(t,x)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

or using the composite function notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\circ u(t,x)=a\circ u_{0}\circ x_{0}(t,x)
\]

\end_inset

However, characteristic curves emanated from different initial points are
 no longer parallel to each other in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution of the IVP is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(t,x)=u_{0}(x_{0}(t,x))=u_{0}\left(x-\left(t-t_{0}\right)a(u(t,x))\right)\label{eq:GeneralSolutionOfQuasilinearWaveEquation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

from which, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can be solved at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,x)$
\end_inset

 in principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Existence of Smooth Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The smooth solution found in the previous section is based upon the assumption
 that the characteristic curves do not intersect with each other.
 Its validness depends on the positiveness of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{a}{x_{0}}:=\dv{a}{u_{0}}\dv{u_{0}}{x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subset\mathbb{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

 is an open interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x_{0}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{a}{x_{0}}>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall p_{0},q_{0}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}<q_{0}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(t)<q(t)\qc\forall t>t_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
From 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{x}{t}=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\circ u(t,x)=a\circ u_{0}\left(x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{x}{t}=a\circ u_{0}(x_{0})
\]

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{t}(q(t)-p(t))=a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{a}{x_{0}}>0$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}p_{0}<q_{0} & \implies a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})>0\\
 & \implies\dv{t}(q(t)-p(t))>0
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x_{0}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{a}{x_{0}}<0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall p_{0},q_{0}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}<q_{0}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exists t_{*}>t_{0}:p(t_{*})=q(t_{*})\qand\forall t\in(t_{0},t_{*})\colon q(t)<p(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is almost the same as the previous theorem, except for the direction
 of the inequality:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{t}(q(t)-p(t))=a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})<0
\]

\end_inset

The intersecting time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{*}$
\end_inset

 of two characteristic curves emanated from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{0},p_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t_{0},q_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be solved from 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t_{*})=q(t_{*})$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}p_{0}+\left(t_{*}-t_{0}\right)a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})\\
=q_{0}+\left(t_{*}-t_{0}\right)a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{*}-t_{0}=-\frac{q_{0}-p_{0}}{a\circ u_{0}(q_{0})-a\circ u_{0}(p_{0})}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When two characteristic curves intersect, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 will have two values
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=u_{0}\left(p_{0}\right)\qand u=u_{0}\left(q_{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which are generally inconsistent.
 Such inconsistency will leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv{u}{x}\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv{u}{x}$
\end_inset

 can be solved from
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t,x)=u_{0}\left(x-\left(t-t_{0}\right)a\circ u_{0}(x_{0})\right)
\]

\end_inset

as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u}{x}=\frac{\dv{u_{0}}{x_{0}}}{1+\left(t-t_{0}\right)\dv{a}{x_{0}}}
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth, the condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv{u}{x}\to\infty$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+\left(t_{*}-t_{0}\right)\dv{a}{x_{0}}=0
\]

\end_inset

which leads to the 
\noun on
intersecting moment
\noun default
 when the characteristic curve emanated from a 
\emph on
specific
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 intersects with some other characteristic curve:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{*}=t_{0}-\left(\dv{a}{x_{0}}\right)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

The real 
\noun on
breaking moment
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A natural question is: what will happen after the breaking moment.
 If we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(t_{b},x_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 as the IC of a new IVP, it will become a generalised Riemann problem, which
 will be discussed in the section of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "subsec:RiemannProblems"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\noun default
 of the smooth solution is the minimum of all these intersecting moments:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{b}=t_{0}+\min_{x_{0}\in\Omega}-\left(\dv{a}{x_{0}}\right)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

