\begin_layout Plain Layout

[Structure of Self-Similar Solution]
\end_layout

\end_inset

The self-similar solution of a system of conservation laws has the following
 structure: it contains 
\begin_inset Formula $(m+1)$
\end_inset

 constant regions, which are connected by 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 elementary waves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our task is to determine the properties of these elementary waves, such
 as type, speed, strength, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Shock Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A shock wave is a discontinuity where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 changes abruptly, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{F}$
\end_inset

.
 The change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{F}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the jump condition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:JumpConditionFor1dSystem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The entropy condition is satisfied with strict inequal signs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\lambda_{k}(-)>s_{k} & >\lambda_{k}(+)\\
\lambda_{k-1}(-)<s_{k} & <\lambda_{k+1}(+)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, it implies the characteristic curves on both sides run into
 the discontinuity curve.
 Physically, it implies there are mass/momentum/energy flowing across it
 with entropy increasing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Rarefaction Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A rarefaction wave is a region where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 changes smoothly, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Any 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 in this region is an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Matrix{A(U)}$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{\ket{U}}{\xi}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding right eigenvector, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\dv{\xi}U_{1}}{\ip{1}{R_{k}}}=\cdots=\frac{\dv{\xi}U_{m}}{\ip{m}{R_{k}}}=:\alpha
\]

\end_inset

There are 
\begin_inset Formula $(m-1)$
\end_inset

 generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-Riemann invarians that are constants along the trajectories of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{R_{k}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{W}{\xi}=\ip{\nabla W}{\dv{U}{\xi}}=\ip{\nabla W}{R_{k}}\alpha=0
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-characteristic curves diverse from each other, that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dv{\lambda_{k}(\xi)}{\xi}\ge0\qc\xi\in[\xi_{-},\xi_{+}]
\]

\end_inset

in which, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{+}$
\end_inset

 is the speed of the wave head, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{-}$
\end_inset

 is the speed of the wave tail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Contact Discontinuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A contact discontinuity is a discontinuity where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 changes abruptly, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{F}$
\end_inset

.
 The change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{F}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the jump condition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:JumpConditionFor1dSystem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, the entropy condition is satisfied with equal signs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\lambda_{k}(-)=s_{k} & =\lambda_{k}(+)\\
\lambda_{k-1}(-)<s_{k} & <\lambda_{k+1}(+)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Geometrically, it implies the characteristic curves on both sides are parallel
 to the discontinuity curve.
 Physically, it implies there is no mass/momentum/energy flowing across
 it, and of course no entropy increasing.
\end_layout

